of line the bright trim was of a similar layout to that of the cavalier the skirt mouldings being carried over virtually unchanged although roof quarter glazing was a common option on cavaliers the less rounded roofline of the grenadier ensured grenadiers with this option were rare  salesedit the first two grenadiers were a reliance  for harris of greys and a leopard psu for grey green both of which were shown at the  earls court commercial motor show in the initial season a further  ft reliance  went to abbott of blackpool two leopards to gliderways of smethwick five to northern general the only bet order and a unique  ft grenadier went to hawkey of newquay on a reliance  with specially reduced front and rear overhangs it was registered saf and sat   salesedit for the  season a  ft in option for the shorter chassis was introduced  of these went to six bet companies and seven independents previous harrington customers were north western southdown trent and timpson of catford southdown specified the dash panels of the cavalier on their batch the return of north western was maybe a surprise as they were a major supporter of the m alexander y type but they obviously wanted something shorter and a bit classier for their extended tours their two leopard l had illuminated offside and nearside name badges under the second bay the two new bet customers were western welsh and black  white motorways of cheltenham both taking short reliances straw of leicester had previously taken the cavalier and specified a cavalier dash on its reliance conquest sales for the short grenadier in the independent sector were to jones of aberbeeg birch brothers and motorways overseas both of london roman city of bath and wye valley of hereford the first three operators took reliances and the latter two tiger cubs roman citys was a rebodied  exribble coach whilst wye valleys two new examples had  coach seats not possible using harrington seats so plaxton seats were purchased and fitted for the lo